    {
      "fullUrl": "urn:uuid:be3a6157-f62b-426f-ba5a-299e49c16a87",
      "resource": {
        "resourceType": "Communication",
        "status": "completed",
        "text": {
          "status": "generated",
          "div": "<div xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml\">patient-description</div>"
        },
        "category": [
          {
            "coding": [
              {
                "system": "urn:virpat:fhir:doc-type",
                "code": "patient-description"
              }
            ]
          }
        ],
        "subject": {
          "reference": "urn:uuid:11111111-1111-4111-8111-111111111111"
        },
        "payload": [
          {
            "contentString": "{patientName} is a 68-year-old retired civil engineer from Brno, Czech Republic. He is a broad-shouldered man of average build, though he has noticed some weight gain over the past year. He lives with his wife of 40 years in a comfortable apartment near the city centre; their two adult children visit regularly on weekends. Since retiring five years ago, {patientName} enjoys gardening, weekend hiking in the Moravian hills with friends from his former workplace, and playing chess at a local club. He is a non-smoker and drinks one or two beers at the weekend only.\n\n{patientName} first presented to his urologist roughly two years ago with increasing lower urinary tract symptoms — a weak urine stream, nocturia two to three times per night, and a feeling of incomplete bladder emptying. A markedly elevated PSA prompted further investigations including a prostate needle biopsy, which confirmed a malignant neoplasm of the prostate [MEDDIALOG:C61:0]. Staging workup showed high-risk disease based on his Gleason score and PSA level [MEDDIALOG:C61:0]; a pelvic CT and bone scan were performed. He subsequently underwent a radical prostatectomy at the Masaryk Memorial Cancer Institute in Brno [MEDDIALOG:C61:0].\n\nPost-operatively, {patientName} was commenced on intermittent hormonal therapy combining leuprorelin (an LHRH agonist) and bicalutamide (an anti-androgen), consistent with the management of high-risk prostate cancer [MEDDIALOG:C61:0]. PSA monitoring is conducted at regular intervals; a PSA value above 0.2 ng/mL would indicate biochemical failure [MEDDIALOG:C61:0], and the treating team remains attentive to this threshold. His most recent PSA was 0.05 ng/mL, which is reassuring. He tolerates treatment reasonably well, though he reports hot flushes and mild fatigue related to androgen deprivation.\n\nIn addition to his oncological management, {patientName} has a longstanding history of hypertension managed with lisinopril, atenolol, and amlodipine [MEDDIALOG:C61:4]. He monitors his blood pressure at home and attends his general practitioner in Brno quarterly. He finds the combination of his cardiac and oncological medications complex but adheres carefully to his regimen with his wife's support."
          }
        ]
      }
    },
    {
      "fullUrl": "urn:uuid:9ac5a931-f931-4087-bce8-8b250698c326",
      "resource": {
        "resourceType": "Communication",
        "status": "completed",
        "text": {
          "status": "generated",
          "div": "<div xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml\">patient-history</div>"
        },
        "category": [
          {
            "coding": [
              {
                "system": "urn:virpat:fhir:doc-type",
                "code": "patient-history"
              }
            ]
          }
        ],
        "subject": {
          "reference": "urn:uuid:11111111-1111-4111-8111-111111111111"
        },
        "payload": [
          {
            "contentString": "{patientName} was diagnosed with high-risk prostate cancer (Gleason score 8, PSA 18.4 ng/mL at baseline) approximately two years ago following a prostate needle biopsy [MEDDIALOG:C61:0]. He underwent radical prostatectomy at the Masaryk Memorial Cancer Institute, Brno [MEDDIALOG:C61:0]. Post-operative pathology confirmed pT3a disease. Adjuvant pelvic radiation therapy was subsequently administered given his high-risk pathological features [MEDDIALOG:C61:0]. He has been on intermittent hormonal therapy (leuprorelin + bicalutamide) since surgery [MEDDIALOG:C61:0].\n\n{patientName} has a 15-year history of arterial hypertension managed with lisinopril 20 mg twice daily, atenolol 100 mg twice daily, and amlodipine 5 mg twice daily [MEDDIALOG:C61:4]. He has no history of diabetes mellitus, coronary artery disease, or cerebrovascular events. He has never smoked and has a low-to-moderate alcohol intake. His BMI is 27 kg/m². He has no prior hospitalisations other than those related to his urological condition. He has a known allergy to amoxicillin (skin rash). His father died of prostate cancer in his mid-seventies."
          }
        ]
      }
    }
  ]
}